Analysis on prosper loans dataset¶

by Aaron Ghanim¶

Investigation overview: The Aim of the analysis is to explore relationships between the variables relating to characteristics of prosper loan customers, with special attention to features influencing the Borrowing Rate offered to a loan customer.

The project logical structure is as follows;

Univariate analysis:

  • BorrowerRate Distribution
  • Distribution of credit score
  • Loan term count plot
  • Distribution of income range
  • Distribution of loan original amount

Bivariate analysis:

  • Rate vs. Credit score scatter plot
  • Rate vs. Loan term violin plot
  • Rate vs. Income Range
  • Additionally, heatmap and correlation matrix

Multivariate analysis:

  • Pairwise relationship between Rate, score and loan amount
  • Scatter with color bar, Rate Vs Score vs Term
  • Subplots of displot Rate, Income range and credit score
  • Subplots of boxplot of Rate, Income range and term
  • Violin of rate vs income vs term

Data Wrangling¶

Prosper loans are small type loans typically below the value of $35,000. With a maximum loan repayment term of 60 months. Data for 113937 loans customers has been collected and represented below. The data is collected over a period oof 8 years 2007-2015.

Columns of interest for the purpose of analysis. Reasons for choosing these variables are availability of data with reasonable amount of missing values, they are data types facilitating quantitative and qualitative analysis and finally variables with potential of explaining the variable of most interest; being BorrowerRate:

  • ListingNumber 'Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.'

  • ListingCreationDate 'The date the listing was created.'

  • Term 'The length of the loan expressed in months.'

  • CreditGrade 'The Credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.'

  • LoanStatus 'The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.'

  • BorrowerAPR 'The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.'

  • BorrowerRate 'The Borrower's interest rate for this loan. '

  • LenderYield 'The Lender yield on the loan. Lender yield is equal to the interest rate on the loan less the servicing fee.'

  • Occupation 'The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.'

  • IsBorrowerHomeowner 'A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.'

  • CreditScoreRangeLower 'The lower value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.'

  • CreditScoreRangeUpper 'The upper value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency. '

  • OpenCreditLines 'Number of open credit lines at the time the credit profile was pulled.'

  • TotalInquiries 'Total number of inquiries at the time the credit profile was pulled.'

  • TotalTrades 'Number of trade lines ever opened at the time the credit profile was pulled.'

  • IncomeRange 'The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.'

  • LoanOriginalAmount 'The origination amount of the loan.'

  • MonthlyLoanPayment 'The scheduled monthly loan payment.'

  • LP_CustomerPayments 'Pre charge-off cumulative gross payments made by the borrower on the loan. If the loan has charged off, this value will exclude any recoveries.'

Dataset ready for analysis!¶

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: BorrowerRate.

In [13]:
# Distribution plot
x_ = loans['BorrowerRate']
sns.displot(data = loans,x = x_, aspect = 2);
plt.title('Distribution of Borrowing Rates offered by prosper Loans');
plt.ylabel('Count');
  • The distribution represent a bi-modal distribution at 0.15 and 0.30 approximately. Denoting that these two rates are the most common for prosper loan customers.
  • The distribution is slightly skewed to the right, indicating that there are some outliers, i.e. customers charged an interest rate above 0.35

Next, the first predictor variable of interest. Credit Score.

In [14]:
# Since the minimum credit scores lie in a range [300, 900] I will set that to be the x-axis
x_ = loans['CreditScoreRangeUpper']
sns.displot(data = loans, x = x_, bins = 100, aspect = 2);
plt.xticks([300, 350, 400, 450, 500, 550, 600, 650, 700, 750, 800, 850, 900]);
plt.xlim([300, 900]);
plt.title('Distribution of prosper loan customers Credit Scores');
  • Majority of customers credit scores lie between the 650 and 750 range, with the mean value being approximately 700.
  • The left skes of the distribution suggests that most loan customers are anxious to maintain a rellatively good credit score.
  • For more information on credit scores check: https://www.experian.com/blogs/ask-experian/credit-education/score-basics/what-is-a-good-credit-score/

Next, second predictor variable of interest. Loan Term.

In [15]:
# Since a customer has a choice of 1 of 3 possible loan terms, a count plot would be appropriate 
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
x_ = loans['Term']
sns.countplot(data = loans, x = x_);
plt.title(' Three possible loan monthly Terms');
  • The most popular loan term among prosper loan customers is the 36 months. Followed by the 60 months term and finally the 12 months.
  • Note that it is more profitable for the loan provider that customers select a longer term loan, since they gain more interest over time.

How about the distribution of income range?

In [16]:
# Create a dictionary with ordered income ranges
ordinal_var_dict = { 'IncomeRange' : [ '$0', '$1-24,999','$25,000-49,999',
                               '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+',
                              'Not employed', 'Not displayed' ]}

# initiaite a loop to change variable type
for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loans[var] = loans[var].astype(ordered_var)

Bivariate Exploration¶

Initially, examine the relationship between BorrowerRate and Credit Score.

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
x_ = loans['BorrowerRate']
y_ = np.log(loans['CreditScoreRangeUpper'])
sns.scatterplot(data = loans, x = x_, y = y_)
plt.ylim([5.5, 7.5]);
plt.title('Relation between Borrower Rate and the Credit Score of a customer');
  • Initial exploration suggests that no correlation is apparent between a customers credit score and the rate they are charged, but could there be more to it?!

How about the relationship between BorrowerRate and the Loan Term

In [21]:
# a violet plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.violinplot(data = loans, x = loans['Term'], y = loans['BorrowerRate']);
plt.title('Relationship between Borrower rate and Terms');
  • The most variation in borrowing rate is associated with the 36 months term.
  • Borrowing rates variation is approximately uniform across the 12 and 36 months terms.
  • However, for the 60 months terms; borrowing rates tend to be distributed with a skew to the left, towards lower rates.

Further, examining the cumaltive distributions of loan term

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
# a plot of the cumilative distributions of the three loan terms
x_ = loans['BorrowerRate']
y_ = loans['Term']
sns.ecdfplot(data = loans, x = x_, hue = y_, );
plt.title('plot of the cumilative distributions of the three loan terms');
  • The cdf distribution function indicates that 12 month loans have the lowest borrowing rate.
  • Whereas 36 and 60 months have a higher borrowing rate, surprisingly, 36 and 60 months loans have similar borrowing rates on average.

plt.title('Grid plot of numeric variables');
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10));

<Figure size 720x720 with 0 Axes>

Multivariate Explorations¶

The aim of this section is to inspect the interactions between Borrower Rate and other variables of interest.

First, observing the relationship between Borrower Rate vs Credit Score vs Loan Original amount

In [27]:
# pairwise relationship between Rate, score and loan amount
vars_ = ['BorrowerRate', 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper']
g = sns.PairGrid(loans[vars_], aspect = 2)
g.map_upper(sns.histplot)
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot, fill=True)
g.map_diag(sns.histplot, kde=True) 
plt.title('Pairwise relationship between Rate, score and loan amount')
Out[27]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Pairwise relationship between Rate, score and loan amount')
  • No clear correlation is apparent, however it could be seen that as the Loan original amount increases, borrower rates falls.
  • Also, as the credit score tend to rise, so does the amount borrowed by the customer.
  • However, again no clear effect of credit score or loan original amount can be observed on borrower rate.

Furthermore, cross influence of Credit Score and Term on Borrower Rate.

In [28]:
# plot examining the effect of loan term and credit score borrower rate
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8));
plt.scatter(data = df, x = 'CreditScoreRangeUpper',
            y = 'BorrowerRate', c = 'Term', cmap = plt.cm.viridis);
plt.colorbar();
plt.title('Rate vs Score vs Term');

Here, it is clear that a combination of short term, and high credit score (which is usually associated with large loan amount) grants a customer the cheapest borrowing rate. This result does not take into consideration few outliers, whom are obtaining a very low borrowing rate approaching 0.00. Such customers, probably supported by certain government shcemes or recieving employee's discount for example.

Additionally, observing the joint effects of credit score, loan term and adding income range.

In [29]:
# Construct plots to compare effect of income and loan term
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
sns.kdeplot(
   data=loans, x="BorrowerRate", hue="IncomeRange",
   fill=True, common_norm=False, palette="crest",
   alpha=.5, linewidth=0);
plt.title('Distribution of Rate based on Income Range');

# Second plot
plt.subplot(2, 2, 4)
sns.kdeplot(
   data=loans, x="BorrowerRate", hue="Term",
   fill=True, common_norm=False, palette="crest",
   alpha=.5, linewidth=0);
plt.title('Distribution of Rate based on Loan Term');

# Third plot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.kdeplot(
   data=loans, x="BorrowerRate", hue="CreditScoreRangeUpper",
   fill=True, common_norm=False, palette="crest",
   alpha=.5, linewidth=0, warn_singular=False);
plt.title('Distribution of Rate based on CreditScore');
  • Clearly, income range has an effect on the skew of the borrower rate distribution, implying an effect.
  • As for the loan term, most effect can be noticed with the 60 months term with a clear centre at approximately 0.17. Followed by the bi-modal distribution of the 36 months term, probably because its the most popular loan term, it has the biggest spread over the borrower rate range.
  • A clear disparity in the rate charged can be observed between customers with high credit scores represented by shades of blue, and those with lower credit scores represented by shades of green.
  • a negative correlation is observed between credit score and borrower rate.

Next, examine the effect of Income Range and Loan Term on borrower rate.

  • As expected, the unemployed loan customers are charged a higher rate than employed customers.
  • Finally, a few outliers are drawn to attention for customers with Not displayed source of income.
  • Regarding the income range vs. loan amount a weak positive correlation can be observed, however, a large number of outliers exist for each category, suggesting that loan issuers are faced with a hard evaluation process.

Next, it would be interesting to examine the cross influence on borrower rate by loan's term, in addition to, the customer's income range.

# Rate vs Income vs Term
sns.catplot(x="BorrowerRate", y="IncomeRange", hue="Term",
            kind="violin", bw=.15, cut=0,
            data=loans, aspect = 1, height = 10);
plt.title('Rate vs Income vs Term');
  • For those with income range of $75,000+ , a short term loan mostly grants them a cheaper borrowing rate than those with lower income levels, and also cheapre rate than those within the same income category but who opted for a longer term loan.
  • As for customers with no displayed source of income, it become extremely difficult for loan issuers to assess a fair rate to charge, hence the great disparity.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Prosper loan customers come from various backgrounds, with various occupations, income ranges and credit histories. Hence, it becomes a highly complex task for the loan issuer to generate an exact evaluation of the loan amount, rate and terms a customer should be offered. Therefore, prosper loan providers decided that it simplifies the task to assess each customer mainly based on their credit score and the term length of the loan. Income range of the customer also has an effect to be considered. The outliers present in the data also suggest that; borrowing rate is evaluated ad-hoc. This result is inline with the real world, try going online and getting an initial loan quotation, and you will be asked for those variables!
